WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:02.700
and says, how do I get to Dublin?

00:02.700 --> 00:04.980
And the answer that comes back is,

00:04.980 --> 00:07.040
well, I wouldn't start from here, sonny.

00:09.320 --> 00:13.520
That is to say, much of political philosophy

00:13.520 --> 00:18.520
develops theories that take no account of...

00:19.984 --> 00:23.024
where we actually are and how the theories

00:23.024 --> 00:25.284
that people argue about in the journals

00:25.284 --> 00:27.844
and in the literature actually could be implemented

00:27.844 --> 00:29.324
in the world, if at all.

00:29.324 --> 00:32.724
And this spills over into normative arguments

00:32.724 --> 00:35.764
made by other scholars.

00:35.764 --> 00:40.764
Thomas Piketty in his book Capital in the 21st Century

00:41.984 --> 00:46.984
argues for a 4% global wealth tax.

00:46.984 --> 00:50.484
Well, good luck with that.

00:50.528 --> 00:54.468
Who's gonna implement a 4% global wealth tax?

00:54.468 --> 00:59.468
So I, when I think about normative questions,

